lex array of stakeholders who work in and profit from a media sector, and models a variegated examination of the history of media industries. Ultimately, it draws a parallel to the contemporary period and the introduction of digital media to highlight the fact that history repeats itself and can therefore play a key role in helping media industry scholars and practitioners to understand and navigate contemporary industrial phenomena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCopyrightxBroadcasting rightszUnited States. 0aLicense agreementszUnited States. 0aMotion picture audienceszUnited States. 0aMotion picture industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxDistribution. 0aTelevision broadcasting of filmszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision viewerszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  ascreenwriter, screenwriting, writing, writer, television, tv writer, television writer, script, film, filmmaker, film writer, movie writer, screenplay, hollywood, mel brooks, carl reiner, norman lear, screenwriters' guild, screenwriters guild, broadcasting, media, communications, American studies, American film, film studio, film networks, advertising, advertising agencies, guilds, theatre, theatre associations, FCC, TV ratings, television industry, 1940s, 1950s, digital media, contemporary, postwar industrialism, intermedia, convergence, transmedia, media industry studies, early TV.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081359625940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813596259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813596259/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutg